{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532640"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:28:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:28:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14696"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14696"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.69,0.03,0,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60346"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7389"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45768"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1875"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2665"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45937"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60346"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive exertional dyspnoea over six months. She has rheumatic heart disease diagnosed in childhood. She takes warfarin and metoprolol. On examination, she appears short of breath on minimal exertion. Her pulse rate is 85/min and irregular, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals an opening snap and a mid-diastolic murmur. Chest examination reveals fine bilateral basal crackles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram shows severe mitral stenosis with valve area 1.0 cm2, mean gradient 12 mmHg, and significant leaflet thickening with heavy calcification and subvalvular involvement. The Wilkins score is calculated as 10/16.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct current cardioversion","Surgical mitral valve replacement","Medical management with diuretics only","Increase metoprolol dose","Percutaneous balloon mitral valvuloplasty"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic severe mitral stenosis, confirmed by echocardiographic findings of valve area 1.0 cm2 and mean gradient 12 mmHg. The high Wilkins score of 10 indicates significant valve degeneration with calcification and subvalvular involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical mitral valve replacement\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. The high Wilkins score (\u0026gt;8) makes her unsuitable for percutaneous intervention due to the high risk of procedural complications and poor long-term outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous balloon mitral valvuloplasty\u003C/strong\u003E would be the preferred option for patients with suitable valve morphology (Wilkins score \u22648), but in this case, the heavily calcified and degenerated valve makes this approach unsuitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing metoprolol dose\u003C/strong\u003E may help control symptoms temporarily by reducing heart rate and improving diastolic filling time, but it will not address the underlying severe mechanical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical management with diuretics\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate for severe symptomatic mitral stenosis. While diuretics may temporarily improve symptoms, they do not address the underlying mechanical obstruction and would not prevent disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect current cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E might help if atrial fibrillation is present, but it would not address the underlying severe valve stenosis, which is the primary problem requiring intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Wilkins score assesses valve morphology based on four parameters: leaflet mobility, thickening, calcification, and subvalvular involvement. Each parameter is scored from 1-4, with higher scores indicating more severe pathology. A total score \u0026gt;8 generally predicts poor outcomes with balloon valvuloplasty, making surgical valve replacement the preferred option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with severe mitral stenosis and high Wilkins score (\u003E8) are not suitable candidates for percutaneous balloon mitral valvuloplasty.","Surgical valve replacement is indicated for symptomatic severe mitral stenosis when percutaneous intervention is contraindicated.","Echocardiographic features of severe mitral stenosis include valve area \u003C1.5cm2 and mean gradient \u003E10mmHg."],"references":["Vahanian A, Beyersdorf F, Praz F, et al. ESC/EACTS Scientific Document Group. 2021 ESC/EACTS Guidelines for the management of valvular heart disease. Eur Heart J. 2022;43(7):561-632. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/eurheartj/article/43/7/561/6358470"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45768"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14696"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45768"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T23:48:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-26T09:29:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7389"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60346"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":n